<TITLE> Cabinet okays draft tourism law </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 7 (bdnews24.com)--The cabinet has approved a draft on tourism law, styled Bangladesh Reserved Areas for Tourism and Special Tourism Zones Act-2010. It also adopted a motion of condolence over the Nimatali and Begunbari tragedies, the prime minister's press secretary Abul Kalam Azad told reporters after the regular meeting on Monday. Cabinet secretary MA Aziz placed the condolence motion in the meeting. The cabinet members also prayed for peace and salvation of the departed souls. About 150 people died in two incidents of Nimatali blaze and Begunbari building collapse last week. It then prayed for peace and salvation of those who died during the movement to realise the six-point charter of demands in 1966. The six-point day is being observed on Monday in remembrance of the people who sacrificed their lives for the realisation of the demands that led to birth of Bangladesh in 1971. Monday's cabinet meeting rejected National Hajj Policy (1431-1435 Islamic calendar) and Hajj Package of 1431 hijri (amended), he added. It ratified the framework agreement on trade facilitation in APTA participating states and the framework agreement on the promotion, protection and liberisaiton of investment in APTA participating states. Azad did not elaborate them. 
